  "statement_md": "The exam cell just printed your hall ticket — and your name on it is wrong. Panic first, then walk to the office: the clerk's software can fix the name, but it charges per **fix operation**, and one fix operation does exactly one of these:\n\n- **insert** one letter anywhere in the name\n- **delete** one letter from the name\n- **replace** one letter with a different letter\n\nYou are given the name as printed (`P`) and your correct name (`C`), both in lowercase letters. The clerk wants to press as few buttons as possible.\n\nPrint the minimum number of fix operations needed to turn the printed name into the correct name.",
  "input_format_md": "The first line contains a single integer `T` — the number of test cases.\n\nFor each test case:\n- the first line contains the printed name `P`\n- the second line contains the correct name `C`",
  "output_format_md": "For each test case, print a single integer — the minimum number of fix operations — on its own line.",
  "constraints_md": "- `1 ≤ T ≤ 5`\n- `1 ≤ |P|, |C| ≤ 800`\n- both names contain only lowercase English letters `a`–`z`\n- the total length of all names in one input does not exceed `5000`",
  "hints": [
    "Compare the two names from the front. If the first letters already match, that position costs nothing and both names shrink by one. If they differ, exactly one operation — an insert, a delete, or a replace — must deal with it, and each choice leaves you with a smaller version of the same problem.",
    "Build a table where cell `(i, j)` is the minimum operations to turn the first `i` letters of `P` into the first `j` letters of `C`. Each cell needs only its top, left, and diagonal neighbours — so you never need more than the previous row in memory, and the whole thing is `O(|P| × |C|)`."
